Hey boys, I went into the Marine Corps recruiting office at 17, they took one look at my ASVAB and called me every single day telling me I could have any job in the Marines I wanted, all the way up until I left for Air Force boot camp, asking if I still wanted to be in the Marines. OH! But, now that I remember it, in basic training there was this monster of a dude whose recruiter had told him that he could try out for special forces once he was in, but the recruiter never told him his ASVAB was too low to be in special ops. This dude was a physical specimen. His muscles had muscles, but the Air Force wouldn't even let him try out because his ASVAB was too low. If you've never seen a 6 foot muscle pile crying, it's not something you want to see. I felt SO BAD for him. He JOINED to be special ops. Ended up a fucking mechanic or something.

OH and it doesn't even matter what job you even get trained for. I signed up to be a computer programmer, was trained as a computer programmer, then spent 4 years in Honor Guard. This was in 1988.  We had two different locations. The first was an old muddy pig farm, stunk to high heaven. Mud everywhere. The second was right next to a graveyard. In the graveyard, there were these huge stacks of hay. We were told (I don't know if this was true) that because the ground was frozen, if someone died, they would just put the body on the ground and then all the hay over it until the ground thawed. So here is this tent city butting up against this graveyard with all of these dead bodies. Not really an ideal location. The worse though was Thailand. Uggh. Muggy wet heat is just miserable. I'm from canada. As a 15 year old I was in cadets. The first year I went to cadet camp on the navy base, there was an issue with are plane so we had to spend the night at a naval base till we could catch the next flight. We slept on the floor of the officers bar that night. No blankets no pillows, just your luggage. Camp gives you those and personal items can be taken or stolen so no one brought these. On our wilderness training we slept on the mountian with thin long "tarps" zippered together. The "make shift tent" was tied to trees because the ground was solid rock, and we were expected to dig a trench to keep dry. We did this for 2 days, and on the second night there was a nasty storm. The officers told us we only needed to zipper the top tarps, but not to fasten the bottom to the top, we were soaked and frozen, probably because no one listened to me and also put the "tent" with the biggest opening facing the top of the mountian. This is what real military training is like. And I was the oldest at 15 years old (or her than the officers)

I'm sure the military is completely different now, as compared to the '82-'90 timeframe, when I was in. Drill Sergeants beat you, (in the showers), if you screwed up enough. "Blanket parties" were an all too common occurrence. I was lucky, I was young (16) and had more stamina and grit than most. I turned 17 two weeks before graduating basic training, to make it legal. I felt badly for the older guys.

An example of the head games they'd play; One morning when we were at a rifle range, our Drill Sergeants noticed their "pet" hadn't made his bed properly. They decided to throw all 150+ beds, (everything, but the frames), plus our extra boots, out the windows. (We lived, on the 3rd floor). By the time we returned, some 7, or 8 hours later, all our bedclothes were blowin' in the wind. Each day, it was something new.


That being said, my military experience was great... Stateside. It wasn't until I shipped to Germany, that I realized there was a different Army there.

According to the Stars and Stripes; 1/15th INF BN, 3rd ID (The unit i was in, in Germany), had; the most A.W.O.L.s, the most attempted suicides, (there were 6 guys sleeping at the CQ desk, when I initially got there), the most cases of aids, (it was still a thing), and strange enough, the most pedestrians hit by train. (Guys would jog on the tracks, apparently the wrong way, while listening to their Walkman... Go figure).

During the "Cold War", awards and rank were hard to get. Stateside, I went to Air Assault school. Made E-5 (Sgt.), in 27 months, (depending on your job, it normally took from 2 to 5 years). I got 4 Army Acheivements and 6 Commendations. Plus, I had the "added bonus" of spending a few months, in El Salvador, where I got a Purple Heart, thanks to Reagan.

Then I did 5+ years, in Germany. Spent 2 of those years with only 2 hours off, per night. Another 2 years, (broken up into 3-month "field problems"), sleeping in a tent, in the woods. Just to get away from the "Erk & Jerk" crew. If you don't know, E&J is a brandy popular with minorities.

Just to be asshats, my leave requests were denied for 4 years. It took an act of Congress for me to get the pay i had coming. (You accrue 30 days per year. If not used, you lose them). I was denied each time for the same reason, my "participation was essential to the completion of the mission". Just a weasel way to say we were understaffed and being the only white guy, I constantly got passed over for promotion and leave.

Looking back, if I'd have listened to rap music and drank E&J I'd have been OK, but I was young and ignorant, of the ramifications of not enjoying those things. I considered it a challenge and never broke. However, I did contract pneumonia when I was attached to a unit doing cold weather training, in the Alps. Had both eardrums ruptured whilst attached to an M109 howitzer unit.

Needless to say, I got no promotions. The only awards, for work I did attached to other units. 2 Acheivements (both for REFORGER missions) and 3 Commendations.

For the record; My name is, Don Reno. I hide from no one. My moniker is a genuine question. Why is that waste of air still alive? Please tell me. Certainly, he's crossed paths with real men, who saw through his grift, and graft, through the years, and not the spineless "yes men" he's surrounded himself with since the early 2000's.

Swarming kids are no goddamn joke, man. So - true story. And yes it's relevant.

In the U.S. Marines, doing a mock war in the Norwegian city of Trondheim with the Dutch, Germans and other allies, training in urban combat. My infantry unit was positioned in a large soccer field next to an elementary school. Keep in mind there was no actual combat, even simulated; it was mostly just practicing maneuvers and tactics. But we still looked out of place with weapons and gear, etc. It's fucking February. In Norway. Cold as balls. Snow up to our knees. Norway obviously has no snow days, so the kids were all in school.

Anyway, so Norway has this most delicious and amazing delicacy, I have no idea what it's called, but it's basically a bacon-wrapped hot dog; we just assumed it was called Candy of the Lord. As Americans we were naturally and instantly addicted. You find them at gas stations, and there just happened to be one on the other side of the school where we were camped. A few of my fellow Marines and I requested permission to go to the gas station and we set out on our way.

We made it to right about where the main entrance of the school was, and the doors opened; school was out. There were only a few kids, probably 6 or 7 years old. Lots of talking and laughing. Gawking at us as we walked by, with our guns and huge ridiculous snow suits. One precocious little bugger made shooting noises at us. We made shooting noises back.

And then someone in my group. I don't know who. God help me I don't know who...

Someone threw a snowball and hit a little girl in the leg.

And those little Norwegian children unleashed hell.

There was a shrill cry in unintelligible gibberish and the doors to the school burst open. School children flooded out like a never-ending flood of something that never ends. Screeching, smiling, sprinting - how the fuck were they sprinting?? - little bastards were slinging snowballs faster than the laws of physics should allow. It was like that movie Elf. If you can imagine riding in a fast car in a snowstorm and sticking your head out the window. Now imagine the snowflakes that are hitting your face are the size of snowballs. We couldn't fucking see. We couldn't run. We could barely breathe. Holy fuck....

We tried to return fire and threw one, maybe two half-packed, shitty snowballs that fell apart in the air, arms flailing like limp-wristed fairies. I am from Texas. We were a unit stationed in North Carolina. We were so outmatched and out of our element, it only made them laugh harder. We were cutoff from our main forces. We tried to perform a flanking maneuver but fuck me they were fast. I think some of them were throwing rocks!

My comrades. I could see them speed waddling in their huge suits back to camp like a fucked up pair of white Teletubbies, under withering fire. Fuck tactics, fuck me, fuck the Candy of the Lord, this was survival! I was the slow one in the group. My snowboots were too big but they were the smallest size they had at Issue goddammit!! My Marines left me behind.

I tried pulling my hood over my head and keeping my head down. No longer content to pelt my defenseless body with ballistic snow, the enemy swarmed me and dragged me down, cackling like a pack of hyenas descending on a wildebeest. I tried to sling them off by spinning. I came out of one of my boots and fell. I began to scream and plead for them to stop but they neither understood nor gave a single Nordic fuck. They literally pinned me down with about five kids on each limb. It was then that I actually thought - oh shit. I'm really in trouble. My snow-mittens were ripped off and flung into trees. They started shoving snow down my suit. Have you ever had anyone drop an ice cube down your shirt?

Well now imagine someone shoveling handfuls of ice cubes down your shirt. It literally shocked the breath out of my body. Thisishowidie.jpg.gif

They left me laying like a Family Guy accident victim. Moaning and screaming in the cold. Rifle packed with snow and dirt. Boot buried some-fucking-where. They ran away laughing, jabbering in their crazy language. I lay there trying to figure out just what in the great American fuck had happened.
